Looking for Evidence of Climate Change in Minimum Temperature Trends

ww44ss

September 30, 2014

Synopsis

Trends in minimum temperature are thought to be among the most telling signatures of climate change. This analysis tests that hypotesis by looking for this signature in climate data stored by NOAAs National Climate Data Center.

The analysis looks at a couple of statistics, including the trend of daily minimum temperatures over the length of the record and a trend of the number of days each year with temperatures above the median low temperature and above 0oC for the entire sample.

TempData <- read.csv("407175.csv", header=TRUE, na.strings="-9999")

Data Input and Cleaning

Input and data cleaning are pretty straight forward. Data are downloaded from the National Climate Database by selecting
- Browse Data Sets
- Daily Summaries
- Mapping Tool - Selecting a station with an appropriately long record (preferably 1930s to present)
- Select Custom GHCN-Daily CSV - Select Date Range
- On next screen select Station Name and Air Temperature (contains fields TMIN, TMAX, and TOBS)
- Enter email address
- Submit

A link to the data will arrive in your email in a few minutes to a few hours.

One the file is dowloaded it can be stored in the local directory. The program needs to be edited to read it.

The main data cleaning are eliminating NAs and creating Date factor columns for later analysis.

The cleaned data contain 27598 observations from 1930-02-01 to 2008-10-31.
The maximum high temperature during this period was 40.6 degrees Celcius.

The maximum low temperature during this period was 33.3 degrees Celcius.
The minimum low temperature during this period was -15 degrees Celcius.

Trend of Low Temperatures for SEASIDE OR US

The Temperature trends for a specific location show expected seasonal variation and seems to follow a regular pattern with little apparent long term change.

The plot below is the TMIN data for the period mentioned above. In most cases a few data points which appear to be outliers are present. These points are not eliminated from the analysis since there is no documented reason to do so.

We can disect the seasonal trend from the data as in the plot below. Ranges vary but for most coastal data sets the variation in low temperatures is on the order of 10oC. This variation will swamp any expected changes (more on the order of 1oC) from climate change.

Looking at Trend in the Winter Months

One place to start is looking at the trend of Min temps in the Winter months. From the graph above, the TMIN for the Months December to March are fairly stable. So lets start there.

Density Trends

The first thing to look at is the density of temperature data points for each year of the record. In the Figure below each TMIN is plotted with an alpha = 0.06, meaning that about 15 overlaying data points can be resolved. Here, , though the trend line shows little to no variation, we can possibly see a hint of an upward trend in the data suggested by a lower density of points at the low end in later years.

## geom_smooth: method="auto" and size of largest group is >=1000, so using gam with formula: y ~ s(x, bs = "cs"). Use 'method = x' to change the smoothing method.

Min Temp Trends

library(plyr)

##Get data for select months 
TempDataWinter<-TempData[TempData$MON== "Mar"|TempData$MON == "Dec"|TempData$MON == "Jan"|TempData$MON == "Feb",]
##Get the median of the tire endata sets
TMINWintermedian<-median(TempDataWinter$TMIN)
##Selet the data records below the Median
LowData<-TempData[TempDataWinter$TMIN>TMINWintermedian,]

##count the total records
TMINtotal<-count(TempDataWinter$TMIN, "YEAR")
##count the selected records
TMINsubcount<-count(LowData, "YEAR")

##normalize measurement to number of measurements per year
TMINsubcount$freq<-365.*TMINsubcount$freq/TMINtotal$freq

##store the selected records in a holding variable.
TMINcountLOW<-TMINsubcount

       P1 <- ggplot(TMINsubcount, aes(x=1930+as.numeric(TMINsubcount$YEAR), y=freq))+geom_point(colour="red")
       P1<-P1+stat_smooth(method="loess")
       P1<-P1+xlab("YEAR")+ylab("Number of Days")+ggtitle("Winter TMIN > Median vs. Date") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))
#+ coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 200)) 

print(P1)
